generalfeedback.text:
We can obtain the information that we require by inspecting the graph. Looking at the graph, the turning point is the vertex of the graph which is the point \((1,-9)\). Clearly this is a minimum and the parabola is concave upwards.

The axis of symmetry is the vertical line which passes through the turning point. Therefore it is the line with equation \(x = 1\).

Recall that the roots of the quadratic correspond to the points at which the curve crosses the \(x\)-axis. We can see that on this graph the two roots are therefore \[ x = -2 \qquad \mbox{ and } \qquad x = 4. \]
